                    "company": "University of Amsterdam",
                    "description": "My PhD research (ongoing) looks at the way in which the 'traditional' donors of foreign aid - the members of the OECD Development Assistance Committee (DAC) - respond to the recent increase in Chinese financing to Africa. In the context of this research project I have conducted extensive field research in Zambia, Ghana and Uganda. The research is conducted within the Department of Political Science at the University of Amsterdam.\n\nI have taught several courses, including the Bachelor Thesis Project 'The rise of the BRICS: from North-South to South-South Relations?' and the tutorials for the courses 'Core Module International Relations and 'Political Economy'.\n\nI was also part of the joint research program: 'The Transnationalization of China's Oil Industry' between the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences (CASS), the International Institute for Asian Studies (IIAS) at Leiden University and the Royal Netherlands Academy for Arts and Sciences (KNAW). Within this program I studied China's involvement in Ghana's emerging oil industry as well as the interaction between Chinese national oil companies and Ghana's political settlement since the country's oil discoveries in 2007.",
